<span id="freeTextContainer14919066316026844488">There&apos;s a quote in this book contrasting politics (&quot;the great generalizer&quot;) with literature (&quot;the particularizer&quot;) and while this book has a great many memorable characters in it, the overall feel is that these particular fabrications run dangerously close to serving as pawns in a generalized, polemical debate. Roth gives us Ira Ringold firmly planted in the McCarthy era to explore so much through a deeply flawed character, but much of it is told secondhand in ways where other characters heavily</span>
  <span id="freeText14919066316026844488" style="display:none">There's a quote in this book contrasting politics ("the great generalizer") with literature ("the particularizer") and while this book has a great many memorable characters in it, the overall feel is that these particular fabrications run dangerously close to serving as pawns in a generalized, polemical debate. Roth gives us Ira Ringold firmly planted in the McCarthy era to explore so much through a deeply flawed character, but much of it is told secondhand in ways where other characters heavily summarize, armchair psychoanalyze, and explain Ira to the reader.<br /><br />Roth does a wonderful job of capturing and rooting a particular time and place in American history. And a three-star Roth is pretty much a 4-star anybody-else, but given my fondness for the other two books in this trilogy, this one felt a bit too pedantic.<br />---------------------------------------<br />WORDS I LOOKED UP BUT PROBABLY WON'T USE DURING THE COVID-19 PANDEMIC<br /><a href="https://www.dictionary.com/browse/chiropodist" rel="nofollow noopener">chiropodist</a> | <a href="http://www.yiddishslangdictionary.com/word/338/schmatta" rel="nofollow noopener">schmattas</a> | <a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/picayune" rel="nofollow noopener">picayune</a> | deprofanation | <a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/minatory" rel="nofollow noopener">minatory</a> | <a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rostrum" rel="nofollow noopener">rostrum</a></span>
