    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_867150818" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/867150818" />
    <a title="John Pappas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5899347-john-pappas"><img alt="John Pappas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1320586950p2/5899347.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/867150818?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Pappas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Pappas" href="/user/show/5899347-john-pappas">John Pappas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer867150818" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2812411244654361563">How do you process a big, bombastic, messy book like this? On the surface, a scant plot: Ira Ringold&apos;s wife, Eve Frame, outs him as a Communist in a tawdry memoir. Roth&apos;s perennial narrator-cum-alter ego, Nathaniel Zuckerman, interviews Ira&apos;s brother to see what really happened in those Cold War days. The result? Complex and conflicted characters torn between the promises of various idealisms and the harder realities of their hypocritical desires: bourgeois comfort, power, sex and revenge. Roth&apos;</span>
  <span id="freeText2812411244654361563" style="display:none">How do you process a big, bombastic, messy book like this? On the surface, a scant plot: Ira Ringold's wife, Eve Frame, outs him as a Communist in a tawdry memoir. Roth's perennial narrator-cum-alter ego, Nathaniel Zuckerman, interviews Ira's brother to see what really happened in those Cold War days. The result? Complex and conflicted characters torn between the promises of various idealisms and the harder realities of their hypocritical desires: bourgeois comfort, power, sex and revenge. Roth's unique narrative structure, trenchant critiques of the media and political machines and use of literary (Hamlet) and historical allusion (the end of chapter eight's comparison of Nixon's funeral with the aforementioned Russomanno's canary's funeral) is relevatory, and his depth of characterization engenders a nigh-allegorical account of the shifting sands of American values, the multivalent uses of propagandistic<br />tropes and, simply, the sadness of human nature compared to the ideals it authentically and duplicitously upholds for itself. Ira, with his rage and his ideals about the brotherhood of man, becomes, or is rendered, what he hates-- a capitalist, a shell of a man shilling rocks for pennies. An American tragedy: Dynamite.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2812411244654361563" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

