<div id="review_2388700551" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2388700551" />
    <a title="D" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4277032-d"><img alt="D" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1466334351p2/4277032.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2388700551?book_show_action=true">May 17, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="D" class="user" itemprop="url" name="D" href="/user/show/4277032-d">D</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2388700551" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1106583348998837909">A memorable Nathan Zuckerman story. As a youth, he befriends the larger-than-life communist brother of his English teacher who is married to a movie star (just before and during the McCarthy madness). It made me wonder if, perhaps, the relative strength of the US communists/stalinists then might be responsible for the fact that social democracy never caught on in the US (until Bernie Sanders ;).</span>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

